<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="li-comment-73039">
<article id="comment-73039" class="comment">
<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
<img alt='' src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/b0dfbc1f89ee64ca3887f7420af20434?s=44&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/b0dfbc1f89ee64ca3887f7420af20434?s=88&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' loading='lazy' decoding='async' /><cite><b class="fn">Jory</b> </cite><a href="https://allaboutcats.com/best-cat-brush#comment-73039"><time datetime="2022-01-08T05:18:17+00:00">Jan 8, 2022 at 5:18 am</time></a> </header>
<section class="comment-content comment">
<p>I have variations of brushes for my tuxedo , (not short.,not long hair either, hair. A large oval shaped hair brush of mine seems to be her fav, Plastic brush with rubber tips that are on a cushioned like center. Use it softly in various directions that gives a massage to her body and hair, and causes her &#8216;motor &#8216;to start, also causes a roll over to get her tummy as well!! Under the chin and around whiskers and ears are welcomed too. She leans back her head for that. She is about 15 years and runs over when ever I pick up the brush. Also, not every day&#8230;.wash her face and eyes with a warm cloth and wipe the dust off her head from the sand box.</p>
</section>
